post_text:
Garrison Public Schools has made a minor adjustment concerning attendance to events INSIDE the school that affects activities. Masks are required when you come in, but once you are seated in the gym AND if you can maintain 6 feet of physical distance from non-family members, the masks can come off. Please bring your own as we have limited supplies. We ask you hold on to the mask if you visit the concessions or leave the gym. If you cannot distance yourself, the Board is asking people to mask up.
For the volleyball game tonight vs DLB, we have many openings so if you did not get a "Covid Pass" we should be able to accommodate you.
If you are unable to attend, the matches will be on Facebook Live on the Garrison Public Schools site.
Please honor the requests from the Garrison Public School concerning masks. The reality is, failure to comply may affect our ability to have fans attend our events. We want our kids to play and that is the priority with activities.

post_text: This just in: starting 9/2/2020, breakfast and lunch at school is FREE to our PreK-12 students thanks to a waiver extension granted by USDA through 12/31/20 or until funding runs out. post_text:
We have updated our Hybrid Learning Plan based on the Governor's announcement yesterday and after we met with the Department of Health this morning. The level in which we are at specific to COVID, will now be determined at the county level. However, if we have zero active cases or a manageable number of cases, we may elect to go to hybrid learning. These updated changes are now in both the Hybrid Learning Plan and our Safety Plan.

We are hopeful we are able to make these determinations locally, since county numbers have an immense variability. However, this piece has yet to be determined by the state and we are waiting on further guidance.
text:
We have updated our Hybrid Learning Plan based on the Governor's announcement yesterday and after we met with the Department of Health this morning. The level in which we are at specific to COVID, will now be determined at the county level. However, if we have zero active cases or a manageable number of cases, we may elect to go to hybrid learning. These updated changes are now in both the Hybrid Learning Plan and our Safety Plan.

We are hopeful we are able to make these determinations locally, since county numbers have an immense variability. However, this piece has yet to be determined by the state and we are waiting on further guidance.

Dr. K. here with a couple things...

1. Thank you everyone with your continued flexibility, as we are in uncharted territory.

2. We have amazing students! I couldn‚Äôt be more proud of them.

3. We have an amazing staff who go above and beyond!

4. Huge shout out to our maintenance staff for all their hard work this summer. Our buildings look incredible!

Since we are not able to have an open house at this time, I‚Äôm sharing some pictures of the remodel. Please note, the same flooring, paint, and lighting is the same throughout both buildings. Our remodeling in both buildings is at about 95% completion with some small things still needing to be addressed. However, I will say our buildings sure do clean up nice! I can‚Äôt wait for the time for our community to get a chance to see it in person.

Since we are not able to have an open house at this time, I‚Äôm sharing some pictures of the remodel. Please note, the same flooring, paint, and lighting is the same throughout both buildings. Our remodeling in both buildings is at about 95% completion with some small things still needing to be addressed. However, I will say our buildings sure do clean up nice! I can‚Äôt wait for the time for our community to get a chance to see it in person.

post_text:
This is Mrs. Larson and she will be teaching first grade this year. She grew up and graduated from Drake, ND. and then went on to get her Early Childhood and Elementary Education degrees from the University of Mary. Since then she taught first/second grade in Bowbells, kindergarten in Garrison and then kindergarten in Max. Her and her family live in Max and they have two little boys. She recently graduated from UTA with my Masters in Education, so she am excited to start her next teaching adventure in Garrison as the first grade teacher. She loves that she gets the opportunity to come back and teach with such wonderful people again in Garrison. Life took her to another school for a while but coming back she knows will benefit her family and grow her skills as a teacher. She's excited to have a co-teacher again and work as a team to make this year amazing! This summer has been filled with spending as much time with her family at the lake camping. Camping is pretty new to them, but her boys have been loving every second of it!

Please welcome back Mrs. Larson!

post_text:
All...

This afternoon we received an outline of the guidance for plans moving forward with our schools at the same time all of you did. We have not seen the specifics referenced in the press conference; however, there were some details shared during the press conference. What we do know is we will be required to submit a safety plan and another distance learning plan. Both of these plans will require input from a variety of stakeholders throughout our community. A general outline for both plans will be completed and the stakeholders will then assist in the development of the finer details. Both the school board and the state will need to approve of these plans moving forward. Ultimately, this will all take time to digest and complete knowing we will do the best we can for our students, staff, and community. Thank you in advance for your patience. More to come...

Dr. K.

News from the Prom Committee concerning this years prom:

Unfortunately GHS will not be able to have prom this year. There is still an executive order restricting the number of people to 15 people per room within a school. Sorry for the delay in the announcement but we were hoping more restrictions would be lifted.

Other communities are having prom through parent-led initiatives that are not on school grounds. If there is a group interested in doing this, we could arrange for the already-purchased prom decorations to be used.

post_text: Welcome to GHS Graduation. It is going to be a phenomenal day. Ceremony starts at 2:00. You can catch it on Garrison Facebook page and on Zoom.

post_text:
Based upon the current forecast, we are moving forward with graduation inside our gymnasium. We will only be allowing the graduates and their parents to attend the ceremony. Chairs have been set for our students and parents adhering to the guidance. Parents will have assigned seats, as they will be handing out the diplomas to their child. Please enter through the west doors of the gymnasium starting at 1:15 for parents. Graduates need to be at the school by 12:00. The ceremony will still be on FacebookLive, Zoom, and will be recorded. Hand sanitizer stations will be set up upon entry and all are expected to maintain social distancing. The locker room will be used for bathrooms. We understand this may not be the ideal graduation, but we are doing are best given the current situation.

Respectfully,

Dr. Nick Klemisch

Reverse Parade to Celebrate the Class of 2020:
On Sunday we will hold a reverse parade for the graduates. In a reverse parade the graduates will be sitting on Main Street. The city of Garrison will do the drive by to honk, cheer, and celebrate the accomplishments of this years class. Line up behind the Garrison Police Chief and SRO Dave Kamp at 2:45 at the Wally the Walleye on the north end of Main Street. After graduation the parade will begin when the graduates are in place and on Main Street. We hope to see everyone there. Mr. Dangel

All...

Graduation will be on Facebook Live and zoom. We will also be recording it and it will be aired on our local RTC channel, as soon as they are able to upload it. The zoom link will be going out in an email later this week and posted to a variety of sites; however, we are recommending you watch it on Facebook because it can handle a larger volume of people to watch it.

Regarding graduation, only parents and siblings will be allowed on the football field. The first row of parking will be reserved for parents of graduates along the practice field offering a good view. We will be using an outdoor audio system, so it should provide for better sound. All of this is of course is contingent upon weather. The forecast is calling for rain. In the event it rains, graduation will be moved into the high school gymnasium. If this occurs, only graduates and parents will be allowed into the gymnasium and we will zoom, facebook live, and record the ceremony for others to see. We will make this decision on Saturday afternoon.
Thank you.

post_text:
Here is some exciting and awesome news from our FFA chapter:

Good Afternoon!!

We have some very exciting news to share from the FFA chapter!

Aaron Johnson has been selected as a State Star Farmer finalist and Skyla Folden has been selected as a State Star in Ag Placement finalist! Both individuals have earned their spots as finalists due to their passion for agriculture and their work in their Supervised Agricultural Experience (SAE) projects. As a finalist, they are in the top two in the state that submitted an application in their award area. Each individual will be submitting a video of their SAE and we will be waiting to hear who the State Stars are, which will be announced the first week of June. Congratulations Aaron and Skyla, we are so proud of you!!

post_text:
Last week a survey went out to all juniors and seniors concerning prom. There were 3 questions asked:
1. Grade ‚Äî We had 36 respond, 18 juniors and 18 seniors
2. Would you attend prom in June? We had 83% respond yes and 17% said no
3. Should we cancel prom? We had 69% respond no and 31% said yes

Students have spoken. As a school we have decided our make-up date for prom will be Tuesday June 30. This date was chosen over a weekend out of respect for families that may want to go camping. We have been quarantined in our houses a long time. If we are up and moving families will want to get out of the house. We also decided on the last day in June. This will give the governor time to open up ND. It also allows us time to see what, if any repercussions may occur from social distancing measures being lapsed. The safety of all who attend is our top priority.

Thanks for your understanding and we are all hoping that prom will happen in June.

Thanks Mr. Dangel

post_text:
The NDHSAA Activities Board met this morning. The recommendation coming out of that meeting in regards to Winter Sports Tournaments, Fine Arts, and Springs Sports is continue to suspend until further notice. CDC guidelines of social distancing carry us through April. The Board will be meeting again on Friday, May 1st to discuss further. From the discussion we can tell you that if on-site school happens to resume then there is certainly a possibility of some of these things happening. If school does not resume this year - the likelihood of these events happening is quite slim.

In other news from the meeting. The board approved to move forward with sanctioning E-Sports as a NDHSAA sponsored activity. What this looks like still needs to be determined. But it is the hope of the NDHSAA to have this up and running for the 2020-2021 school year.

post_text:
Since the Governor‚Äôs announcement on Sunday night that K-12 schools would be closed, our teachers have been working vigorously to get ready for what many feared was coming. In an effort for families and staff to prepare , we believe it‚Äôs best to move forward with this plan. Therefore, we will begin our blend of learning alternatives on Monday, March 23rd. Specific classroom questions can be communicated later this week to your child‚Äôs classroom teacher. Please email nick.klemisch@k12.nd.us
with discussion points you may have and I will put together an FAQ to answer those questions the best we can. Deployment of materials and tech devices will go out as planned tomorrow. All staff will continue to report as we have done this week.

PS we still do not have updates on spring activities, prom, and graduation. Our hope is the curve will flatten soon and we will back to normal. Thank you for bearing with us as we enter uncharted educational territory.

ND Department of Public Instruction
March 13 at 11:54 AM ¬∑

A statement from Kirsten Baesler, the North Dakota state school superintendent, about the Department of Public Instruction's response to COVID-19:

"NDDPI is working with the Governor‚Äôs Office, the North Dakota Department of Health, and the North Dakota Department of Emergency Services to draft guidance for our schools. We are working as quickly as possible, while ensuring that we provide the most accurate and up-to-date information. We hope to have something out by the end of the day (Friday, March 13, 2020). During these times, it is critical that the relationship between all State agencies and local education agencies (schools) be strong and that all communication be coordinated, consistent, clear and thorough. We recognize there are many questions. We appreciate your patience as we work through the necessary state level coordination."

UPDATE: Here is the text of a Department of Public Instruction memo sent to schools today: https://www.nd.gov/dpi/nddpi-guidance-covid-19

Reminders....

Thursday PT Conferences will begin at 4:00 at the elementary school. All elementary students should have a scheduled time and grades 7-12 will be the elementary gymnasium.

Saturday from 6-10 pm we will be hosting a backyard game night for grades 7-12. If you have corn hole boards and bags, ladder golf, etc... we can use please send them with your child. Also, we will have some classrooms available for video games. Gaming systems will also have to brought by students. Food and beverages will be provided along with smores to be made by students. The purpose of this night will be to provide students with an opportunity to do constructive activities during the weekend. Please encourage your children to come, as it should be a great time.

Please share!!!
